description:

description: This planting site is found to be highly deteriorated, which means it will need an important enrichment job. We did find some ecologically important species, but when it comes to structure, the area is scarce. Its estimated area is about 9 hectares.

description: Until recently this was a tree-lined country lane that provided biodiversity and wind shelter for local wildlife. These trees had to be felled due to safety concerns. This project is to replace this area with native boundary hedges.
name: Plumford Lane - Faversham (Kent)

description: The land is part of the Blue Cross Animal Sanctuary, whose owners want to plant trees to improve the environment for local people and the animals. The planting by community groups and schools will be a combination of native woodland and hedgerows.
name: Blue Cross 1-Burford (Oxfordshire)

description: 5000 native trees on a large scale (13ha) site near Glasgow, part of Cathkin Braes Country Park. 1120 trees are planted by local community groups and ITF volunteers; the other trees are planted by local school children. Maintained by Glasgow City Council.
name: Cathkin Braes-Carmunnock (Scotland)

description: Trees replace those lost by Ash Dieback + continue woodland conversion from commercial coniferous to native broadleaf woods. This part of Wales (Pembrokeshire) is largely treeless (deforested for agriculture). New forests are vital for people + wildlife.
name: Ffynone Forest, Newchapel (Wales)

description: This nursery is one of our mayor sources for saplings for our community projects in the UK (mainly in England. Northern Ireland and Wales).
name: Murray McClean Nurseries - Frilford

description: This is our mayor nursery supplying saplings for our Community projects located in Scotland and the North of England.
name: Alba Nurseries - Gladsmuir

description: The project plants + protects native saplings by creating a mature woodland with a broad range of habitats. The protected land ensures community engagement with volunteers and the people working together to plant and steward the saplings as they mature
name: Tregothnan Estate- Truro (Cornwall)

description:
After planting 1000 trees in 2021, the local landowners and community groups are planting more trees along public byways and footpaths. 
This will provide habitat for local wildlife, as well as providing shelterbelts for the local fruit farms.
name: Swale (Kent)

description: Habitat restoration of a 126-acre site, located on a working farm that offers environmental education together with residential stays for disabled and other vulnerable groups, which will be involved in planting and learning about the newly planted trees.
name: Magdalen Farm (Somerset)

description: Creation of a hedgerow around a community orchard. This will protect from strong winds, contribute towards increasing pollen for insects, berries for birds, and habitats and food for over 300 species, including the  endangered species, red squirrel.
name: Alyth Hill (Scotland)

description: Transformation of a vacant and derelict industrial park into a multi-use community space to increase social value and native restoration. Will also be used to grow local food and teach the community about how they can learn and gain from nature.
name: Blue Green Glasgow (Scotland)

description: Project epands existing woodland on a farm at the southernmost point of Arran, with expansion to the western edge of the fields, and the woodland to the east. It supports education about local food sovereignty, healthy eating + regenerative agriculture.
name: Arran - North Ayrshire  (Scotland)

description: Creation of a mosaic of copses and hedgerows at one of the largest wildlife rescue and rehabilitation centres in the UK. They now purchased 20 acres of land to create new habitats, an open access visitor centre and a new wildlife hospital.
name: Wildlife Aid - Leatherhead (Surrey)

description: Blackcap is one of the many sites managed by the National Trust that collectively form the South Downs National Park. The Trust is looking to enhance Blackcap through the creation of wood pasture, clump planting, and hedgerows across the site.
name: Nat. Trust-Black Cap (East Sussex)

description: Banbury Trees, a very committed community volunteer group are working with local landowners who are keen to welcome the public on to their land to plant and enjoy the trees and hedgerows. They will also be involved with the tree care and maintainance.
name: Lambert Farm-Banbury (Oxfordshire)

description: The Astall Manor Kitchen Garden (registered Community Interest Company) plants a 220m hedgerow, creating a wildlife friendly boundary hedge + connecting existing areas of high biodiversity. A network of volunteers will help plant and maintain the hedge.
name: Manor K.Garden-Astall (Oxfordshire)

description: The 54 ha site (project phase 2 with TN) lies on the edge of the Cotswolds Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty (AONB), a former farm now owned by the Blue Cross Rehoming Centre. Native woodland + hedgerow species will be planted by local community groups.
name: Blue Cross 2-Burford (Oxfordshire)

description: This small holding site lies directly beside a well known local woodland which attracts walkers + cyclists. The owner wants to extend the natural environment with hawthorn hedges and willow trees (habitat for the local red squirrels and other wildlife).
name: Tir Na Nog - Perth (Scottland)

description: 11 acre smallholding, providing high quality, sustainable food and a space for nature to thrive (shelter belts around both fields + pockets of woodland areas). They want to plant more native trees for increased shelter and more habitat for local wildlife.
name: Suie Fields - Dumfries (Scottland)

description: This smallholding is a learning hub for organic smallholdings. They plant up previously un-grazed areas. The owners have already undertaken extensive tree + hedge planting on the site, and this year’s planting will further support biodiversity.
name: Lint Mill-S.Lanarkshire (Scottland)

description: Foxholes farm is a progressive farm wanting to improve the biodiversity of the site and the connectivity between fields. The community will be involved in the hedge planting and will have opportunities to visit the hedges in the coming years.
name: Leighton Bromswold (Cambridgeshire)

description: This famous beauty spot on the South Downs National Park is owned by the National Trust. The planting will enhance the landscape with additional copses, wood pastures + hedgerows. This is a publicly-accessible spot, well enjoyed due to its fantastic views
name: Fulking Horse Field (West Sussex)

description: Outstanding 20th-century garden, set around a romantic house + ruins, in beautiful woodland. Mixture of neo-classical ruins + well-kept gardens makes this site very popular spot. This project aims to enhance the landscape with planting of native hedgerows
name: Nymans (Surrey)

description: Part of a larger plan to develop the Primary Academy Wildlife Reserve & Community Garden within the West Marsh area of Grimsby, creating a bio-diverse area in the school that improves the local biodiversity and supports the children to appreciate nature.
name: Littlecoates-Grimsby (Lincolnshire)

address: Blue Cross Animal Rehoming Centre, Burford, Oxfordshire
description: Planting of copses and hedgerows to create natural habitat and and wildlife corridors. The planting is all being done by community volunteers, and it aims to reforest former woodlands of the area of Burford.
name: Blue Cross 3-Burford (Oxfordshire)

description: The whole area has suffered a significant reduction in tree and hedge cover with the widening of the road. The proposed planting will provide an extensive hedgerow network and also wooded areas
name: Huntingdon (Cambridgeshire)

description: Working with local communities (the estate comprises a number of villages), the project looks to restore vital linkages between upland and lowland woodlands, and to create new broadleaf forest areas.
name: Lowther (Cumbria)

description: Macknades is a farm shop at the heart of the community in Faversham. The planting represents a new hedgerow alongside a footpath to be enjoyed by the whole community.
name: Macknade, Faversham (Kent)

description: The Djabissa mangrove reforestation site is located south of Mozambique’s capital city, Maputo, along a large channel that leads to Maputo Bay.  Eden now partners with the local community to reforest this massive mangrove estuary.
name: Djabissa

description: There are thousands of farming families in need due to a rapidly changing climate. Hence at this site, we are helping this family with tree planting by paying their wages and promoting sustainable practices. This site has 21 hectares,
name: Kasesa (coming soon)

description: Our aim is to facilitate and supervise the planting of trees using indigenous and adopted tree seedlings to be planted by organization members and distributed to volunteers and some farmers, particularly across rural communities. This site has 14.05 ha.
name: Kaseme (coming soon)

description: The Bufunda Genge Tano site is one of Village forest reserve located in Geita region, found in Bufunda village. The aim of this project is to restore the loss of biodiversity and regain the nature of the Geita Forest Reserve by planting native trees.
name: Bufunda Genge Tano (2024)

description: Due to massive floods from October to mid-December of 2023, this site has been abandoned. Planting earmarked for this site will be moved to Bufunda Genge Tano
name: Nyachiluluma (Abandoned)

description: The main aim is to reduce the cutting of trees. Because trees provide the purified oxygen which is necessary for most living beings and also reduce carbon dioxide which is vulnerable to nature, helping to give us a fresh air. This site has 16 ha.
name: Lubeho (2023)

description: The aim of this project is to reduce the urban heat island effect through evaporative cooling and reducing the amount of sunlight that reaches.
name: Geita town (coming soon)

description: The aim of this technology is to restore degraded forests by planting seedlings in moisture-accumulating trenches that increase the survival rate of plants.
name: Nyakasu (coming soon)

description: This project area in the Amuru district in the North of Uganda contains 17 group clusters, these are usually key local villages, and a list of 549 different groups of local farmers.
name: Amuru District

description: The Gulu district project area in the North of Uganda contains 8 group clusters, these are usually key local villages, and a list of 368 different groups of local subsistance farmers.
name: Gulu District

description: Afforestation of 3 parcels of common land to encourage the population, how to contribute in forest areas in the recovery of degraded soils and through protection: against wind erosion and fires, of the hydrographic network, microclimate + the environment
name: Freguesia De Eirado (2021)

description: In 2014 the Braga City Council started the reforestation of micro-forest areas in urban strategic locations with native forest species, combining leisure aspects with environmental issues. Schools, parish councils, associations are joining  the initiative
name: Monte Picoto - Braga (2021)

description: Project creates a 2,5 ha Forest Park (leisure area and environmental education space for schools) in Municipality of Pinhel, using native species to preserve the Flora and Fauna. Location is next to chapel of pilgrimage Ermida da Senhora das Fontes.
name: Ermida da Senhora d. Fontes -Pinhel

description: Reforestation of land (12 ha) affected by wildfires in 2017 in the territory of the Viseu Dâo Lafôes Intermunicipal Community (CIM), with 14 municipalities. Each municaplity plants the requested trees with volunteers on its common land ("Baldios").
name: CIM Viseu Dâo Lafôes (2022)

description: This project restores the Senhora do Castelo Forest (40h) near Vouzela after severe fires that devastated 70% of the municipality's area in 2017. Invasive species like eucalyptus and mimosa are replaced by native species more resistant to wildfires
name: Vouzela Mais Verde (2022)

description: Reforesting the banks of the Seia River, after the fires of 2022, with less inflammable species which are more resilient to rural fires.
name: Serra da Estrela Natural Park 2022

description: Creation of areas of high forest density in urban areas intended to be spaces of biodiversity. These will help reduce the heat, improve air quality and  noise levels and increase the infiltration zone of rainwater, thereby reducing flooding.
name: Braga Micro Forest (2022)

description: After a fire in 2017 around the village, the land was reforested in 2022, to recover the burned land and increase the resilience of the territory to rural fires. After one year of its implementation there was some mortality, we are now replanting those.
name: Póvoa Velha (2023)

description: 500 farmers of the Fepromas cooperative located in the regions of Fattick and Kaolack (South West of Senegal) will be trained on sustainable land management practices to restore 125 acres, develop tree nurseries and outplant 500,000 trees.
name: Fattick and Kaolack Region

description:
500 smallholder cocoa farmers located near the towns of Bafoussam, Douala and Yaoundé (Western Cameroon) will grow higher quality
cocoa while improving their land (125 acres) through the intercropping of 500,000 multipurpose trees and fruit trees per year
name: Bafoussam - Douala - Yaoundé

address: R. Dr. José Augusto de Souza e Silva, S/N - Jardim Parque Morumbi, São Paulo - SP, 05712-040
description: Restoring a poket of Atlantic Forest for about 2,500 students in the Unified Educational Center (CEU) Paraisópolis, south of São Paulo. The forest has ~500 m²and more than 1,000 seedlings of native species.
name: CEU Paraisópolis (2022)

description: Creation of a native mini Forest, engaging students and school communities, in the Unified Educational Center Paraisópolis, south of São Paulo. The forest has ~175 m² and among the species planted, there will be several trees with fruits edible by humans.
name: CEU Paraisópolis (2023)

description:
Creation of a native mini forest in the CEU Jose Bonifacio, south of São Paulo, with ~500 sq m.
It’s part of an environmental education program, engaging students and school communities to brings back knowledge about the native Atlantic Forest.
name: CEU Jose Bonifacio (2023)

description: This project re-establishes mixed conifers devastated by the 2020 Lake Wildfire, first reported on Aug. 12, burning 31,089 acres (12,581ha) near lake Hughes.
name: Angeles National Forest

description: The Slater (2020) and McCash Fires (2021) burned 45,000 ha within the Indian and Elk Creek watersheds of the Klamath National Forest. Replanting a mix of native seedlings restores watersheds and revives resistant forests as wildlife habitat.
name: Slater + McCash Fires (Klamath NF)

description: The first planting wave of Jussara Programme is located in 'Assentamento' Dois Riachões, in Ibirapitanga municipality, state of Bahia (BR), in 1 hectare of a plot in the rural settlement. The planting model is a pilot for the other sites of the settlement
name: Assentamento Dois Riachões 1st Plot

description: The first planting wave of Jussara Programme is located in 'Assentamento' Dois Riachões, in Ibirapitanga municipality, state of Bahia (BR). The 2nd Plot has 1,8 hectares, in which the same planting model as the 1st Plot is going to be implemented.
name: Assentamento Dois Riachões 2nd Plot

description: This cluster of subsistence farmers is locted in the county of Embu on the south-eastern slopes of Mount Kenya. The cluster covers an area of 126.1 ha and consists of 67 Groups, 270 Groves and 406 Members
name: Rundu Cluster (Embu county)

description: This cluster of subsistence farmers is locted in the county of Meru, the former Eastern province on the north-eastern slopes of Mount Kenya. The cluster covers an area of 618.8  ha and consists of 191 Groups, 1082 Groves and 1265 Members
name: Kawiru Cluster (Meru County)

description: Bosques de Agua Natural Reserve in the heart of Pampa de Achala at 2,300 meters above sea level, an area of 140 ha, with the capacity to plant 200,000 trees. We aim to restore Pampa de Achala watershed through the reforestation of native highland forests.
name: Reserva Natural BDA 2023

description: Bosques de Agua Natural Reserve in the heart of Pampa de Achala at 2,300 meters above sea level, an area of 70 ha. We aim to restore Pampa de Achala watershed through the reforestation of native highland forests.
name: Reserva Natural BDA (for future)

description: This project regroups farmers in 13 communities to plant 1 million trees in combination with multiple crops (corn, yam, cassava) farming projects.  This project will help increase farmers' crops harvest and improve ecology in the community. Join us!!
name: Bagnabagna, Togo

description: This project is to plant fruit trees in 50 elementary schools in rural communities in Togo (Plateaux). The selected fruit-trees will provide fruits to fight hunger in the community and provide residual revenue for the schools to buy classroom supplies.
name: Fruit Tree in Schools (Plateau, TG)

description: The project is planting trees on the steep slopes in Rukoki sub county to solve the problem of land slides and soil erosion which has claimed lives and degraded land in the area.
name: Kisondo

description: The project plants trees through agro forestry for soil erosion control and land slides
name: Buhaghura

description: The project plants trees for for climate justice in dry lands to reverse the effects of climate change.
name: Kahokya

description: The  restoration project aim to restore areas in advanced stages of degradation including areas in the process of desertification in Kahokya Sub County.  The project has sofa planted 60,000 trees in the areas.
name: Kabirizi

description: The project has planted over 60 thousand trees. The project aim to plant over 200 thousand trees to restore the degraded land on the slopes of Mt. Rwenzori
name: Bughalitsa

description: This plantation is located 2.5km from Mlola center. It covers the area of  about 8 ha, aimed at planting 8880 trees for the purpose of land upgrading and improving life standards of local societies through aggro-forestry and food security inclusively.
name: Mbula (coming soon)

description: This site is located 1km from Lwandai village center. it covers the total area of about 10ha, the objective is to plant 8880 trees to resolve increasing rate of land degradation and soil erosion in the area which caused by poor environmental conservation.
name: IKOI (coming soon)

description: The site is located over the hill 3km from Mlola center.  it covers the area of about 87.5ha, which aimed to plant 97125 trees for conservation and fauna protection purposes. Also environmental education is provided to improve local people's awareness.
name: KWEMFUMBII (2023)

description: The site is located beside Kwekagunga hill and Mdando stream joints. It covers an area of about 50ha which is aimed at planting about 55500 trees for conservation and reforestation purposes to restore the lost biodiversity for natural ecology of the area.
name: KAUZENI RESERVE (coming soon)

description: This is located 1.5km from Mlola town center. it covers the total area of about 35ha, the objective is to plant 38,850trees to resolve the increasing desertification of the area which is caused by deforestation activities and poor environmental awareness.
name: Mnarani planting siite

description: Since 2016 the bark beetle increased its population and affected more than 500 hectares of forest endangering several species. We work on land (mostly protected) with committed private owners inside & outside the National Park.
name: La Malinche (2023)

description: Biodiversity conservation: project plans to restore this area which has been degraded due to illegal logging activity. The ecosystem has a unique allay of habitats including mangrove forests, seagrass meadows, and mudflats which support myriads of fauna.
name: Kadaina Island Mida Creek (2023)

description: Sabasaba area in Mida Creek have been facing deforestation over the years due to poverty level in the area, COBEC team has come up with a restoration plan that engages the local community in planting and also educating them on importance of conservation.
name: Sabasaba, Mida Creek (coming soon)

description: Mtwapa Creek location (3º 55' S, 39º 45' E). It is a tidal creek lined by mangrove forests and extensive mudbanks. The creek receives fresh water input through a seasonal river. Causes of degradation illegal logging, charcoal and building materials.
name: Mtwapa Creek (coming soon)

description: This site is part of the Mindulongan Mountain Range. We are targeting 300 hectares in this site to be planted with fruit and timber trees.
name: Main Planting Site

description: Most of the land here was used for agricultural purposes, is degraded and the soil is exposed to air and hydric erosion. This land is unproductive, and the owners need it to generate income. Therefore, we're developing agroforestry systems in this area.
name: Tlalpujahua, Michoacán

description: Most of the land here was used for agricultural purposes, is degraded and the soil is exposed to air and hydric erosion. This land is unproductive, and the owners need it to generate income. Therefore, we're developing agroforestry systems in this area.
name: Senguio, Michoacán

description: Authorities from the community sought us out to plant in the schools because they are concerned that the boys and girls are straying away from nature. They want to raise awerness of the importance of these species for the community.
name: Donato Guerra, Estado de México

description: The land, 6.5 hec, was used for agricultural and has not been used for some years, although degraded the soil already has plant cover, shrubs and native herbs. The goal by reforesting is to generate ecological and economic benefits for the community.
name: Crescencio Morales, Zitácuaro

description: This area is a mangrove forest area where villagers have joined forces to restore it by planting additional trees. The mission is to conserve and restore natural resources and forestlands, return life and verdancy to Thailand.
name: Mangrover Area - Samut Songkhram

description: Vilcanota River valley is made up of asub-cordillera in the southern Peruvian Andes, whichhouses snow-capped mountains and ecosystemsabove 3,500m elevation. It's inhabited bymore than 20 Quechua-speaking ancestralcommunities, who do community work.
name: Vilcanota

description: We aim to combat the decline of holm oak groves in the Tramuntana region, addressing the effects of climate change and livestock management. The project involves planting new trees and dispersing acorns in a reforested area on Son Torrella's farm.
name: Son Torrella

description: Largest state forest in Georgia (14k ha). Focus on enhancing a native ecosystem that faced recent diseases, insects, and drought. This work provides soil stability, improves water quality, enriches recreational forest use, and supports wildlife species.
name: Dixon Memorial NF (Georgia)

address: Chippewa National Forest, northern Minnesota, USA
description: Chippewa National Forest in Minnesota, home to diverse wildlife and cultural sites, is undergoing replanting to combat environmental challenges and support its thriving American bald eagle population.
name: Chippewa National Forest

address: The Klamath Basin, southern Oregon, USA
description: In 2021, the Bootleg Fire devastated 413,765 acres offorest in southern Oregon, including the Klamath Falls Basin. This area is a hub for biodiversity, including bald eagles, big game, and other small mammals.
name: Umpqua & Fremont National Forest

address: Ozark and St. Francis National Forests, Arkansas, USA
description: The actions will be focused on restoring shortleaf pine in the Ozark Highlands, improving wildlife habitats and transitioning areas from loblolly to shortleaf pine, often alongside oak for mixed-species. This includes areas affected by wind damage.
name: Ozark and St. Francis NF (Arkansas)

description: Gortnaboul is a pastoral landscape used for sheep and dairy farming on the Western coast of Ireland. These have been lost to agriculture over a long period of gradual deforestation.  Once planted, it will become an island of natural woodland habitat.
name: Gortnaboul, County Clare

description:
These are two polygons, one of 37.2 hectares and another of 20 hectares, for reforestation in degraded areas of the Monarch Butterfly Biosphere Reserve.


Son dos polígonos uno de 37.2 ha y otro de 20 ha 

Reforestación en zonas degradadas de la reserva.
name: Nicolas Romero (2 polígonos)

description: Reforestation in degraded areas of the Monarch Butterfly Biosphere Reserve.
name: Ejido Nicolas Romero 65 ha

description: Plantation of 2 million trees with 700 farmers near Mt. Elgon, and training over 4 years. Implement forest gardens stabilizes their lands by planting trees (multipurpose, fruit, and nitrogen fixing trees), intercropped with banana, coffee and vegetables
name: Lwaboba

description: Forest garden projects with 600 farmers that not only restore this critical landscape through plantation of 2 million trees in diverse forest gardens, but also equips farmers with skills (4 year training) to improve soils for fruit + vegetable production
name: Tabora

description: Reintroduction of oak species at the foothills of the Ciomad Volcano. Previously abundant oak trees vanished here due to human activity. Only a few isolated trees remain, and we recolonize this land with 10.000 oak trees
name: Ciomad Volcano (Ciuc Basin)

description: Restauration of previous spruce forests in the Cheile Bicazului Hasmaș National Park to enhance resilience of newly established mixed forests against the impacts of global climate change, particularly on areas previously affected by wind damage.
name: Cheile Bicazului (Hășmaș Mountains)

description: This site located near the Cidamar Village in Cidaun District (Cianjur Regency) with 7661 inhabitants (mostly farmer + fisherman). The lowland terrain has a potential planting area of 884 ha and is now mostly covered with shrubs (avge. farm size 0,75 ha).
name: Cidamar Village - Cidaun District

description: This site located near the Karangwangi Village in Cidaun District (Cianjur Regency) with 6092 inhabitants (mostly farmer + fisherman). The lowland terrain has a potential planting area of 1154ha and is now mostly covered with shrubs (avge. farm size 1 ha)
name: Karangwangi Village-Cidaun District

description: The Tepelmeme Villa de Morelos Commissionerate, located in the Mixteca region of Oaxaca is a community of 2,000 people. Their forests are slowing turning into desert.  This project will restore 85 hectares with 50.000 trees.
name: Las Flores - Tepelmeme (Oaxaca)

description: In 2020 the Red Salmon fire (Klamath NF) burned 58,557 ha of forest. Replanting to restore the natural tree cover is critical for wildlife habitat and watershed health, and supports endangered wildlife species (e.g. coho salmon)
name: Red Salmon Fire (Klamath NF)

description: The Mida Creek mangrove reforestation site lies within UNESCO biosphere reserve. Large-scale mangrove deforestation in this region results from land clearance for salt production, fuelwood, charcoal, and prawns; wild fisheries are also in decline.
name: Mida Creek

description: The Tana Delta is a unique ecosystem providing many natural services and is a biodiversity hotspot for endemic and IUCN red-listed species. Since the 1990s, the Tana Delta has a history of harvesting mangrove poles as trading items and building materials.
name: Tana Delta

description: Kiongwe's mangrove forest has experienced significant changes in canopy cover since the early 19th century. Loss of forest cover was also accelerated by the gradual growth of Kiongwe and reliance on mangrove forests for firewood, charcoal, and building.
name: Kiongwe

description: Historically, Kipini people have used mangroves for building houses, boats, and firewood. Agricultural and irrigation activities along Tana River have also contributed to degradation of mangrove forests. Up to date, the mangrove ecosystem still struggles.
name: Kipini

description: The Tana Delta is a unique ecosystem providing many natural services and is a biodiversity hotspot for endemic and IUCN red-listed species. Since the 1990s, the Tana Delta has a history of harvesting mangrove poles as trading items and building materials.
name: Tana Delta (for future)

description: The Devil's Lake wildfire swept through an area of 200k ha in 2001. Pest infestation such as pine beetle further devastated the forest. 500ha are reforested southwest of Devil's Lake in partnership with seven Swampy Cree Nations (organized as Nakote LP)
name: Devil's Lake Wildfire (Manitoba)
